#X text 455 54 We now have 24 channels of a triangular oscillator with a frequency input and random picthes up and down an octave (updated every 15 seconds with 10 seconds portamento). There are also random pitch and gain variations. For last \, we sum the channels into one with [sum~] and add some overdrive and reverb., f 50;
#X text 178 537 random gain modulation;
#X text 22 26 The [sine~] object from ELSE library (and all the other oscillators from it) takes and generates multichannel signals. As such \, you can consider it also a bank of oscillators and you can perform hard sync \, frequency and phase modulation \, which isn't possible in the previous oscillator bank options. Check it help file for more details. Please note that ALL oscillators from ELSE are multichannel aware \, so you can do the same with all of them., f 56;
#X listbox 80 359 49 0 0 0 - - - 0;
#X floatatom 80 298 5 0 0 0 - - - 0;
#X obj 80 406 f2s~;
#X obj 80 273 initmess 100;
#X text 22 160 In this example \, the frequency of eight oscillators are modulated by independent ramp noise channels. Similarly \, the amplitude is also modulated by independent noise generators. Note that we'll see more about modulation synthesis soon. We have [list.harm] to generate a list of harmonics with a little but of inharmonicity index., f 56;
#X obj 136 427 *~ 0.5;
#X obj 80 328 list.harm 0 8 1.003;
#X obj 136 397 rampnoise~ -ch 8 1;
#X obj 158 508 rampnoise~ -ch 8 3;
#X text 128 459 random variation in hertz (+0.5 to -0.5 hz), f 25;
#X text 204 732 Even though you can use multichannel signals for additive synthesis \, you cannot make it polyphonic unless you have [clone] or something. As an exercize you can try and use [clone] for the both examples above \, as well as having [keyboard] and an amplitude envelope., f 68;
